{% comment %}
  sections/product-grid.liquid
  ------------------------------------------------------------------
  "Tisso vison in the wild" product grid — 6 merchant-selectable
  products (customizer product-picker blocks), 3-col desktop / stacked
  mobile. Built from scratch (no Dawn section reuse), per hard
  constraint in the build-context doc §2.

  Tile content: per the confirmed Figma preview, the grid tile is
  JUST the product photo plus a circular "+" popup-trigger marker —
  no title/price/description/variant controls on the tile itself.
  All of that (name, price, description, color, size, Add to Cart)
  lives only in the popup snippet, opened by that marker.

  POPUP ARCHITECTURE — image-anchored, not a viewport modal:
  Each tile's popup is rendered INSIDE that tile's own
  .product-grid__image-wrap (the same position:relative container the
  "+" hotspot marker lives in), and positioned with
  `position: absolute` relative to that wrapper rather than as a fixed
  full-screen overlay. It is never appended to <body> and is never
  shared across tiles — every product owns exactly one popup instance,
  scoped to its own id, that opens attached to its own image and
  reflows with it at every breakpoint. See the architecture note at
  the top of snippets/product-popup.liquid for the full rationale.

  Depends on:
    - assets/gift-guide.css (shared reset/animation rules, plus the
      absolute-positioning rule that anchors each popup to its parent
      .product-grid__image-wrap)
    - assets/gift-guide.js (Phase 4: color/size selection + add-to-cart
      + Black/Medium → Soft Winter Jacket cross-sell, scoped entirely
      to the popup now that the tile has no controls of its own).
      NOTE: the <script> tag itself is loaded once from
      sections/banner.liquid, since Banner always renders first on
      this page — this file just relies on that script already being
      on the page.
    - snippets/product-popup.liquid (rendered per tile, inside the
      image wrapper, opened via the circular marker's
      data-popup-target; owns all product detail markup and its own
      embedded [data-product-json] script tag)

  IMPORTANT — Shopify schema limitation (read before editing defaults):
  Resource-reference setting types (`product`, `collection`, `page`,
  etc.) CANNOT carry a `default` value in `{% schema %}` — Shopify
  doesn't allow static defaults for anything that references a
  resource by ID, and this applies to block presets too. So the six
  confirmed handles from §4b of the build-context doc
  (olive-green-jacket, chequered-red-shirt, classic-leather-jacket,
  striped-silk-blouse, yellow-wool-jumper, classic-varsity-top) can't
  be wired in as literal schema defaults the way the plan doc implies.

  Fix used here: the `presets` block below pre-creates 6 empty
  `product` blocks so the section looks right when first added in the
  customizer, and the Liquid loop falls back to looking up one of the
  six confirmed handles via `all_products` whenever a block's product
  setting hasn't been explicitly chosen yet by a merchant. Once a
  merchant swaps in a real selection, that takes over automatically.
  NOTE: when this section is placed statically in a JSON template
  (templates/page.gift-guide.json), the template's own "blocks" /
  "block_order" keys are what actually populate section.blocks —
  presets only fire when a merchant adds the section fresh from the
  customizer picker.

  HOTSPOT POSITIONING (per-block, percentage-based):
  Each grid image in Figma has its own "+" marker placed at a
  different spot (it's hand-placed over a specific part of each
  lifestyle photo, not a fixed corner). Two bugs in the previous pass:
    1. The X/Y position was a single pair of *section*-level settings
       shared by all 6 tiles, so every marker landed on the same spot
       regardless of which image it sat on.
    2. Positions weren't reliably expressed as a percentage of the
       *image's own* box, so they'd drift off their intended spot on
       the photo as soon as the tile rendered at a width other than
       whatever the numbers were eyeballed against.
  Fixed by moving `hotspot_x` / `hotspot_y` onto the `product` block's
  own settings (one pair per tile, merchant-editable), and rendering
  them as CSS custom properties consumed by a `position: absolute`
  rule inside a `position: relative` image wrapper — the browser does
  the scaling, no JS/pixel math needed at any breakpoint.

  Default values below were derived by taking each marker's Figma
  frame position relative to its own 433×444 image box and dividing
  by that box's width/height (e.g. image 1's marker sits at
  left: 256.5px, top: 238px inside its 433×444 image → 256.5/433 =
  59.24%, 238/444 = 53.6%). Repeated for all 6 images in the "Tisso
  vison in the wild" Figma frame, in tile order.
{% endcomment %}

{%- assign fallback_handles = "olive-green-jacket,chequered-red-shirt,classic-leather-jacket,striped-silk-blouse,yellow-wool-jumper,classic-varsity-top" | split: ',' -%}

<section class="product-grid__section section-{{ section.id }}" data-section-id="{{ section.id }}" data-section-type="product-grid">

  <h2 class="product-grid__heading">{{ section.settings.heading }}</h2>

  <div class="product-grid__tiles">
    {%- for block in section.blocks -%}
      {%- assign grid_product = block.settings.product -%}

      {%- if grid_product == blank -%}
        {%- comment %} No merchant selection yet — fall back to the confirmed default handle for this slot. {% endcomment -%}
        {%- assign fallback_handle = fallback_handles[forloop.index0] -%}
        {%- assign grid_product = all_products[fallback_handle] -%}
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- if grid_product == blank or grid_product == empty -%}
        {%- comment %} Defensive empty state: neither a merchant pick nor a valid fallback exists. Render a clean placeholder instead of breaking the grid. {% endcomment -%}
        <div class="product-grid__tile product-grid__tile--empty" {{ block.shopify_attributes }}>
          <p class="product-grid__placeholder-text">Select a product in the theme customizer</p>
        </div>
      {%- else -%}
        {%- comment %}
          Hardened against a specific bug seen in production: if
          hotspot_x/hotspot_y ever resolve to nil (e.g. a block saved
          before these settings existed, or any future edge case
          where Shopify doesn't backfill a schema default onto an
          existing block), an inline custom property like
          `--hotspot-x: %;` is a blank/invalid value. `var()` does
          NOT fall through to its fallback in that case — a *declared
          but invalid* custom property makes `left`/`top` invalid at
          computed-value time, which resets them to `auto`. On an
          absolutely-positioned element, `left:auto; top:auto` renders
          at the element's normal-flow position instead — i.e. the
          marker drops out from "pinned to a point on the photo" to
          "sitting in flow right after the image." That exact symptom
          (hollow circle, no icon, parked below-left of each tile) is
          what showed up in a live QA pass, traced back to this.
          Fix: resolve to a guaranteed numeric value in Liquid itself
          (`default: 50`), so the inline style can never be blank —
          this makes the CSS var() fallback below purely defensive,
          not the only thing standing between us and this bug.
        {%- endcomment -%}
        {%- assign hotspot_x = block.settings.hotspot_x | default: 50 -%}
        {%- assign hotspot_y = block.settings.hotspot_y | default: 50 -%}

        <div
          class="product-grid__tile"
          data-product-id="{{ grid_product.id }}"
          data-product-handle="{{ grid_product.handle }}"
          {{ block.shopify_attributes }}
        >
          {%- comment %}
            Photo + popup trigger marker only — all product detail
            lives in the popup, not the tile. Styled as a filled dot
            with a "+" icon per Figma (Ellipse 451 + crosshair vector),
            not a hollow outline circle.

            Positioning: hotspot_x/hotspot_y are percentages of THIS
            image's own box (0–100), set as CSS custom properties.
            .product-grid__image-wrap is the `position: relative`
            anchor and .product-grid__popup-trigger is
            `position: absolute; left: var(--hotspot-x);
            top: var(--hotspot-y); transform: translate(-50%, -50%);`
            — see the {% style %} block below. Because both the
            percentages and the transform are relative to the image
            box, the marker stays visually pinned to the same point
            on the photo at every breakpoint/width with zero JS.
          {%- endcomment -%}
          <div class="product-grid__image-wrap">
            {%- if grid_product.featured_image != blank -%}
              <img
                src="{{ grid_product.featured_image | image_url: width: 900 }}"
                alt="{{ grid_product.featured_image.alt | default: grid_product.title | escape }}"
                loading="lazy"
                width="900"
                height="{{ 900 | divided_by: grid_product.featured_image.aspect_ratio }}"
                class="product-grid__image"
              >
            {%- endif -%}
            <button
              type="button"
              class="product-grid__popup-trigger"
              data-popup-target="popup-{{ grid_product.id }}"
              aria-label="View {{ grid_product.title | escape }} details"
              style="--hotspot-x: {{ hotspot_x }}%; --hotspot-y: {{ hotspot_y }}%;"
            >
              {%- render 'icon-plus' -%}
            </button>

            {%- comment %}
              IMAGE-ANCHORED POPUP: rendered INSIDE .product-grid__image-wrap
              (the same position:relative anchor the hotspot marker above
              uses), not as a sibling of the tile and not as a global/fixed
              viewport modal. This keeps the popup visually attached to its
              own product's image at every breakpoint — see the
              architecture note at the top of snippets/product-popup.liquid
              and the absolute-positioning rule in gift-guide.css. Each tile
              owns exactly one popup instance, scoped to its own product id;
              nothing here is shared across tiles.
            {%- endcomment -%}
            {%- render 'product-popup', product: grid_product -%}
          </div>
        </div>
      {%- endif -%}
    {%- endfor -%}
  </div>
</section>

{% style %}
  .section-{{ section.id }} {
    padding: 4rem 2rem;
  }
  .product-grid__heading {
    font-family: 'Lustria', serif;
    font-weight: 400;
    font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 2vw, 2rem);
    line-height: 1.2; 
    text-align: left;
    margin: 0 0 1.875rem;
  }
  .product-grid__tiles {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: 1.25rem;
    max-width: 1339px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .product-grid__tile {
    width: auto; 
  }
  
  /* Anchor for the absolutely-positioned hotspot below — this is what
  makes hotspot_x/hotspot_y percentages resolve against the image's
  own box instead of some page-relative ancestor. */
  .product-grid__image-wrap,
  .product-grid__image {
    width: 100%;
    aspect-ratio: 433 / 444; 
    height: auto;
    object-fit: cover;
  }

  /* Hotspot "+" marker — 22x22 circle per Figma (Ellipse 451,
    rgba(248,248,248,0.9) fill), position driven entirely by the
    --hotspot-x/--hotspot-y custom properties set inline per block
    (see markup above), never by hardcoded px or nth-child rules.
    translate(-50%, -50%) centers the circle ON the percentage point
    rather than placing its top-left corner there, so the visual
    center of the marker is what actually lines up with the spot the
    designer picked. */
  .product-grid__popup-trigger {
    position: absolute;
    left: var(--hotspot-x, 50%);
    top: var(--hotspot-y, 50%);
    transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
    width: 20px;
    height: 20px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: rgba(248, 248, 248, 0.9);
    border: none;
    cursor: pointer;
    padding: 0;
    z-index: 2;
    color: #000000;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    line-height: 0;
  }
  .product-grid__popup-trigger .icon-plus {
    width: 8px;
    height: 8px;
    display: block;
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  .product-grid__popup-trigger:hover,
  .product-grid__popup-trigger:focus-visible {
    background: #ffffff;
  }

  .product-grid__tile--empty {
    border: 1px dashed #ccc;
    padding: 2rem;
    text-align: center;
  }

  /* NOTE — mobile breakpoint ambiguity: the build-context doc (§4a mobile
    section) describes the "in the wild" gallery as a confirmed 2-column
    layout, but then separately describes the 6 full product tiles as
    full-width single-column at the same 402px Frame 1 width. Now that
    the tile is image-only (no stacked text/controls to widen), this
    reads as the same content at two breakpoints rather than two
    different pieces of content — implemented here as a two-tier
    breakpoint: a wider mobile/tablet tier keeps 2 columns, and the
    narrow 402px tier (matching Frame 1 exactly) drops to a single
    column. Re-check this directly against the Figma mobile frames
    before final submission. The hotspot needs no separate mobile
    handling at all — it's a percentage of the image box at every
    breakpoint, so it stays put as the grid reflows. */
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .section-{{ section.id }} {
      padding: 1.5rem 1rem;
    }
    .product-grid__heading {
      margin: 0 0 1rem;
    }
    .product-grid__tiles {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
      gap: 0.75rem;
    }
    /* Reset desktop's fixed 433px tile/image sizing so mobile's 2-col
      grid tracks (1fr) can actually control width — otherwise the
      fixed px width overrides the grid track and breaks the layout. */
    .product-grid__tile,
    .product-grid__image-wrap {
      width: auto;
      height: auto;
    }
    .product-grid__image {
      width: 100%;
      aspect-ratio: 169 / 186.42;
      height: auto;
      object-fit: cover;
    }
  }
  @media (max-width: 480px) {
    .product-grid__heading {
      text-align: center;
    }
  }
{% endstyle %}

{% schema %}
{
  "name": "Product Grid",
  "settings": [
    {
      "type": "text",
      "id": "heading",
      "label": "Section heading",
      "default": "Tisso vison in the wild"
    }
  ],
  "blocks": [
    {
      "type": "product",
      "name": "Product",
      "settings": [
        {
          "type": "product",
          "id": "product",
          "label": "Product",
          "info": "Pick a product to populate this grid slot. If left unset, one of the six products confirmed for this build (see §4b) is used as a fallback."
        },
        {
          "type": "header",
          "content": "Popup marker position"
        },
        {
          "type": "range",
          "id": "hotspot_x",
          "label": "Hotspot horizontal position (%)",
          "min": 0,
          "max": 100,
          "step": 1,
          "default": 50,
          "info": "Percentage across THIS block's image, left to right. Set per block so each tile's marker can sit on its own photo's focal point — see the Figma reference image for where the marker should land on this product's photo."
        },
        {
          "type": "range",
          "id": "hotspot_y",
          "label": "Hotspot vertical position (%)",
          "min": 0,
          "max": 100,
          "step": 1,
          "default": 50,
          "info": "Percentage down THIS block's image, top to bottom."
        },
        {
          "type": "header",
          "content": "Popup marker position (mobile)"
        },
      ]
    }
  ],
  "max_blocks": 6,
  "presets": [
    {
      "name": "Product Grid",
      "blocks": [
        { "type": "product", "settings": { "hotspot_x": 62, "hotspot_y": 57 } },
        { "type": "product", "settings": { "hotspot_x": 85, "hotspot_y": 53 } },
        { "type": "product", "settings": { "hotspot_x": 64, "hotspot_y": 21 } },
        { "type": "product", "settings": { "hotspot_x": 73, "hotspot_y": 20 } },
        { "type": "product", "settings": { "hotspot_x": 49, "hotspot_y": 26 } },
        { "type": "product", "settings": { "hotspot_x": 77, "hotspot_y": 40 } }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
{% endschema %}
